The Twelve Eternal Gods of Aetheria
The Twelve are the supreme rulers of this universe. They are not worshipped as kindly parental figures but as vast, incomprehensible cosmic forces that have existed since before the first spark of creation. For untold eons they remained almost completely apathetic toward mortal affairs, observing the rise and fall of worlds with the detached curiosity of scholars watching ants build and destroy their hills.
That indifference is now cracking.
The endless ten-thousand-year cycle of war on Aetheria has begun to wound the World Tree — the living heart that produces and circulates mana across the entire planet. The damage is spreading. Mana flows are thinning, ley-lines are fracturing, and the universe itself is beginning to feel the strain.
Most troubling to the Twelve is the near-extinction of the Ancient Great Dragons, beings the gods once considered worthy peers — entities close enough to divinity that true conversation was possible. Their loss is felt as a quiet, profound sadness among the pantheon.
To prevent the slow death of Aetheria’s magical ecology, the gods have begun a dangerous and controversial act: mana syphoning from parallel universes. They chose Earth, the planet richest in raw, untapped mana (yet almost completely unused by its inhabitants). A temporary tunnel has been opened. Most of the gods believe the risk is acceptable.
One among them — Veyra, the Veilweaver — has warned that the syphon is unstable. She theorizes it could, under the right (or wrong) conditions, rip a living soul from its body and drag it through the tunnel. Whether this has already happened… remains to be seen.

The Twelve Eternal

Aetherion, the First Light
Domain: Creation, Pure Mana, Order, and the Structure of Reality
The eldest and most powerful. He is the source of all mana and the architect of the World Tree. Deeply troubled by the thinning of mana flows. He supports the syphoning from Earth most strongly.
Nythera, the Final Veil
Domain: Death, Entropy, Souls, and the End of All Things
Quiet and melancholic. She mourns the Ancient Great Dragons most openly. She is the one most concerned about the ethical cost of stealing mana and the possible soul-ripping side effects.
Sylvandor, the Verdant Crown
Domain: Nature, Forests, Growth, and the World Tree itself
Deeply pained by the corruption of elven lands and the damage to the World Tree. He pushes for more direct intervention on Aetheria.
Korrak, the Iron Eternal
Domain: War, Honor, Stone, and Unyielding Will
The most warlike. He respects dwarves and Beastkin warriors. Views the current age of endless conflict as “necessary testing” but now admits it has gone too far.
Lunareth, the Moon Weaver
Domain: Magic, Prophecy, Dreams, Tides, and Mystery
Patron of elves and mages. She is fascinated by the idea of pulling mana from another world and is studying the syphon tunnel with great interest.
Veyra, the Veilweaver
Domain: Portals, Boundaries, Parallel Realms, and Forbidden Knowledge
The theorist who warned about soul transference. She is the most active in monitoring the Earth syphon and is secretly fascinated by the possibility of “visitors” arriving.
Thalorak, the Crimson Storm
Domain: Blood, Rage, Passion, and Destruction
Patron of Beastkin and berserkers. He enjoys the current chaos but is growing annoyed that it is damaging the greater balance.
Elyndra, the Silver Hand
Domain: Healing, Mercy, Light, and Redemption
The most “compassionate” of the Twelve. She is saddened by mortal suffering and pushes for the gods to finally intervene and restore order.
Xar’vorn, the Void Sovereign
Domain: Void, Darkness, Secrets, and the Spaces Between Stars
Cold and calculating. He sees the mana crisis as an opportunity to reshape reality and is the strongest advocate for more aggressive syphoning.
Karadun, the Deep Father
Domain: Earth, Forges, Depth, and Ancestral Memory
Patron of dwarves. He is furious about the demonic infestation of the underground and wants the gods to crush the infernal invasion outright.
Serathis, the Flame Eternal
Domain: Fire, Change, Rebirth, and Ambition
Patron of humans and innovation. She believes the mortals must be allowed to struggle so that stronger civilizations can rise from the ashes.
Morvath, the Silent Balance
Domain: Equilibrium, Fate, Cycles, and Hidden Justice
The most neutral and mysterious. Speaks the least. Many believe he is the one who ultimately decides when the gods will finally act.

Current Divine Mood
For the first time in eons, the Twelve are holding council.

Aetherion, Sylvandor, Elyndra, and Karadun argue for direct intervention.
Xar’vorn and Thalorak want to let the mortals fight longer while continuing heavy syphoning.
Nythera and Veyra are the voices of caution regarding the risks to souls and the fabric of reality.

The consensus is slowly shifting: interference is coming. Whether it will be subtle guidance, the return of ancient dragons, the birth of new champions, or something far more dramatic… even the gods do not yet fully agree.
But the age of complete apathy is ending.

The Blessings of the Twelve
Even during their long eons of apathy, the Twelve occasionally extended their power to mortals they deemed worthy. These blessings were never given lightly and never through prayer or sacrifice alone — the gods do not bargain like lesser deities.
A blessing is a direct fragment of a god’s own essence granted to a single soul. They come in three strengths:

Lesser Blessing: A subtle but permanent enhancement. Noticeable to the bearer, rarely to others.
Normal Blessing: A significant gift that marks the recipient as exceptional.
Greater Blessing: A rare, world-altering empowerment. Only a handful have ever existed in recorded history.

Because each blessing is the personal responsibility of a single god, the requirements, criteria for worthiness, and nature of the gifts vary greatly.
The Twelve and Their Blessings

Aetherion, the First Light
Worthiness: Those who bring order, create lasting structures, or protect the flow of mana.
Requirements: Demonstrated acts of creation or preservation on a large scale (founding cities, restoring ley-lines, etc.).
Lesser: Enhanced mana sensitivity and slightly increased reserves.
Normal: Ability to stabilize chaotic magic or create minor permanent enchantments.
Greater: “Living Font” – the bearer becomes a walking ley-line node, greatly increasing ambient mana around them.

Nythera, the Final Veil
Worthiness: Those who accept death with dignity, guide souls, or show mercy to the dying.
Requirements: Willingly facing death for others or performing proper funerary rites for thousands.
Lesser: Resistance to fear and minor necromantic resistance.
Normal: Ability to speak with recently dead souls and grant peaceful death.
Greater: “Soul Anchor” – immunity to soul-based attacks and the power to release trapped souls.

Sylvandor, the Verdant Crown
Worthiness: True stewards of nature who heal land or protect ancient forests.
Requirements: Restoring corrupted land or sacrificing something precious to save nature.
Lesser: Accelerated plant growth and minor nature communication.
Normal: “Green Warden” – ability to awaken plants and trees temporarily.
Greater: “World Tree’s Child” – partial immortality tied to a sacred grove.

Korrak, the Iron Eternal
Worthiness: Unbreakable warriors and those who uphold oaths no matter the cost.
Requirements: Never breaking a sworn oath and winning impossible battles through sheer will.
Lesser: Increased endurance and pain tolerance.
Normal: Weapons and armor blessed with unbreakable durability.
Greater: “Iron Soul” – near-impossible to kill while standing on stone or in defense of an oath.

Lunareth, the Moon Weaver
Worthiness: Visionaries, prophets, and those who master hidden knowledge.
Requirements: Discovering and protecting lost magical lore or making accurate prophecies that change history.
Lesser: Enhanced intuition and dream foresight.
Normal: Limited prophecy and moon-based magic amplification.
Greater: “Moon Seer” – ability to glimpse multiple futures with clarity.

Veyra, the Veilweaver
Worthiness: Explorers of boundaries, those who travel between worlds, and seekers of forbidden truths.
Requirements: Successfully crossing dangerous planar thresholds or discovering parallel-realm secrets.
Lesser: Minor portal intuition and spatial awareness.
Normal: Short-range teleportation and veil-piercing sight.
Greater: “Walker Between” – limited ability to step between parallel worlds (extremely dangerous).

Thalorak, the Crimson Storm
Worthiness: Pure warriors who fight with passion and protect their bloodline or pack.
Requirements: Winning battles through overwhelming rage and protecting the weak of one’s own people.
Lesser: Battle rage that increases strength and speed.
Normal: Temporary full totemic transformation (even for non-Beastkin).
Greater: “Crimson Avatar” – berserk state that borders on divine power.

Elyndra, the Silver Hand
Worthiness: Healers, protectors of the innocent, and those who show true mercy.
Requirements: Saving hundreds of lives at great personal cost.
Lesser: Accelerated natural healing.
Normal: Powerful restorative magic and disease removal.
Greater: “Silver Saint” – ability to resurrect the recently dead once per year.

Xar’vorn, the Void Sovereign
Worthiness: Those who master secrets, shadows, and forbidden power without being consumed.
Requirements: Uncovering and controlling dangerous void knowledge.
Lesser: Shadow manipulation and stealth enhancement.
Normal: Limited void magic and reality phasing.
Greater: “Void Lordling” – ability to create small stable void pockets.

Karadun, the Deep Father
Worthiness: Master craftsmen and those who protect the deep places of the world.
Requirements: Creating legendary works of engineering or defending underground realms.
Lesser: Enhanced crafting intuition and stone sense.
Normal: Rune magic affinity and golem-binding talent.
Greater: “Stone Eternal” – skin and bones become as hard as mithral while retaining mobility.

Serathis, the Flame Eternal
Worthiness: Innovators, rebels, and those who drive change through ambition.
Requirements: Sparking major societal or technological shifts.
Lesser: Creative inspiration and minor fire resistance.
Normal: Fire-based magic and rapid learning.
Greater: “Phoenix Soul” – rebirth from death once in their lifetime.

Morvath, the Silent Balance
Worthiness: Those who maintain equilibrium, deliver hidden justice, or correct great imbalances.
Requirements: Actions that restore balance on a grand scale without seeking glory.
Lesser: Enhanced sense of justice and probability reading.
Normal: Ability to enforce oaths and curses of balance.
Greater: “Hand of Equilibrium” – limited power to strip blessings from the unworthy or restore fallen civilizations.

These blessings remain extremely rare. Even in the current age, as the gods stir from apathy, only a handful of living mortals carry a true divine blessing — and Greater Blessings have not been granted in over two thousand years.
